The '''black thicket fantail''' ('''''Rhipidura maculipectus''''') is a [[species]] of [[bird]] in the family [[Rhipiduridae]]. It is found in the [[Aru Islands]] and [[New Guinea]]. This species is one of 47 in the [[genus]] ''Rhipidura''.

== Description ==
This is a medium-sized, long-tailed bird measuring 18-19&nbsp;cm and weighing 18-19&nbsp;g.{{sfn|New Guinea Birds online|ref=NGB online}} The plumage is blackish with white spots on the chest and wings and a white tip to the tail. There is besides a short white stripe above the eye and white spot on the side of the neck. The tail is often lifted and fanned out.{{sfn|eBird|ref=eBird}} The [[Iris (anatomy)|iris]] is dark brown, the beak is black with pinkish underside. Males and females are similar but females have fewer spots and are paler on the abdomen. Juveniles are sooty black all over except for an indistinct white supraorbital spot and white tips on the tail feathers.{{sfn|New Guinea Birds online|ref=NGB online}}

The black thicket fantail is similar to the [[White-bellied thicket fantail]] (''R. leucothorax''), but the latter differs in its white belly (as reflected by its name). This species is also similar to the [[Sooty thicket fantail]] (''R. threnothorax'') which has no white tip to the tail.{{sfn|eBird|ref=eBird}}

== Habitats and behavior ==
The majority of fantails are strong fliers, and some species can undertake long migrations, but black thicket fantails as well as the other thicket fantails ([[sooty thicket fantail|sooty thicket]] and [[white-bellied thicket fantail]]s) are very weak fliers, and need to alight regularly.

Birds of this species are very secretive and it is rather difficult to observe them.{{sfn|eBird|ref=eBird}} Their natural [[habitat]]s are [[subtropical]] or tropical moist lowland [[forest]]s and subtropical or tropical [[mangrove]] forests.

Like other fantails, black thicket fantails are [[Entomophagy|entomophages]]. They usually feed within 1-2 meters from the ground. They catch insects on the fly, by means of horizontal sallies from a low perch.{{sfn|New Guinea Birds online|ref=NGB online}}

The voice is a rising, ringing, metallic song followed by a «wee-chuv!».{{sfn|eBird|ref=eBird}}

